Genesis (Greek Variants file)

Unicode hypertext edition: November, 2005, by Christopher McCartney.
Fully formatted edition "in process" by Robert Kraft (Sept 2007) -- still to do (among other things):

insert special languages (Syriac, Hebrew, Coptic, etc.) and any Greek that remains in Beta Code
disambiguate special codes (e.g. use of %%, of "(2)" and the like)
check places marked with "?" and "??"
-Text and Textual Variants for the Septuagint Book of  Genesis  (Pentateuch): electronic edition (ca 2000, prepared by Fritz Knobloch) -- for  the history of development, see the original Beta coded version and the first unicoded html version.

-This is intended as a resource for free public use, prepared by the Center for Computer Assisted Tools for Septuagint Studies (CATSS) at the University of Pennsylvania, Center for Computer Analysis of Texts (CCAT)

-Filesize uncompressed: about 4.5 meg (also divided into two files to facilitate editing)

-Center for Computer Analysis of Texts (Robert A. Kraft)
Logan Hall, University of Pennsylvania,
Philadelphia PA 19104-6304 USA; kraft@ccat.sas.upenn.edu

PLEASE REPORT CORRECTIONS AND SUGGESTIONS TO R.A.KRAFT AT THE ABOVE ADDRESS

-Bible:OldGreek:Pentateuch:Genesis (001)

This material was prepared under the direction of Fritz Knobloch, and reformats the information in Septuaginta: Vetus Testamentum Graecum auctoritate Societatis Litterarum Gottingensis editum, vol. 1, Genesis, ed. John W. Wevers (Goettingen: Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht, 1974), supplemented with more recent information or discoveries where available. For introductory information on the Goettingen Genesis edition, sigla, etc., see the online English version by John Wevers at http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu/gopher/text/religion/biblical/lxxvar/1Pentateuch/01Gen-Wevers-Intro.html

-The file format as developed for the CATSS LXX/OG Variants Project is described by Robert Kraft, "Treatment of the Greek Textual Variants"
in Computer Assisted Tools for Septuagint Studies (CATSS), vol. 1: Ruth, Septuagint and Cognate Studies 20 (Scholars Press, 1986).

-Categories of variants are introduced thus --
">" = lacking in the following witnesses (a "minus" reading),
"+" = longer text (a "plus" reading),
":" = alternative reading,
< = the following word should be construed before the lemma with which it is associated as a variant, as with definite articles [this needs rethinking],
~ = transpositions, which are treated as plus/minus readings, with "~" added as an indicator

@@@ indicates indentation in the published text [not used in this file]
<it>...</> indicated italics [which now are italicized in html],
and <lt>...</> indicated Latin words and phrases [changed now to italics];
for the Greek transliterations, TLG "Beta Code" had been used [now in Unicode Greek].
-Text divisions were marked by "~" at left margin [now ## for new chapter, # for new verse], followed by "a" to designate the book, "x" for chapter, and "y" for verse; explicit numbers have been added for the user's convenience -- thus "~x2y5" = chapter 2, verse 5 [which now has been simplified to explicit chapter verse designations, with the format ##01 01, #01 02, etc.].

This is the penultimate draft of the text and variants. Queries and calls for verification or correction remain in the old Beta file (in bold type) [update: the bold font did not survive the transition to unicode (see the "beta" version) -- so, Chris McCartney. In some instances, question marks have been inserted to indicate queries], but rather than hold this material back from circulation until there is time and opportunity to edit it more fully, we hereby make it available with this warning about its unfinished character.

Further editing by RAK in August-September 2007, converting italics and superscripts, and joining long strings of witnesses, among other matters.

"LXX/OG-Var"; "001 Genesis"
